{"parse":{"title":"Claasen's law","pageid":20978747,"revid":814571467,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>Claasen's <b>logarithmic law of usefulness</b><sup id=\"cite_ref-EDNarticle_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-EDNarticle-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> is named after technologist Theo A. C. M. Claasen, who introduced the idea in 1999 when he was CTO of Philips Semiconductors:\n</p>\n<dl><dd>Usefulness = <a href=\"/wiki/Logarithm\" title=\"Logarithm\">log</a>(Technology)</dd></dl>\n<p>The law can also be expressed as:\n</p>\n<dl><dd>Technology = <a href=\"/wiki/Exponential_function\" title=\"Exponential function\">exp</a>(Usefulness)</dd></dl>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Examples\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Examples</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Relation_to_Moore&#39;s_law\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Relation to Moore's law</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Notes\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Notes</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#See_also\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">See also</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Examples\">Examples</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Claasen%27s_law&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Examples\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>System parameters (e.g. RAM, CPU speed, disk capacity) need to increase by a multiple to create a noticeable impact on performance. In the case of RAM, by the law, a 256MB unit is only <sup>1</sup>/<sub>8</sub> more practically useful than a 128MB unit though the base unit has doubled. It would require a 16384MB (128 \u00d7 128MB) unit of RAM to truly double performance under the law.\n</p><p>A modern car (e.g. a Ford Mondeo) is not substantially more useful at getting the occupants from A to B than an older car (e.g. a <a href=\"/wiki/Ford_Model_T\" title=\"Ford Model T\">Ford Model T</a>)\n</p>\n<h2><span id=\"Relation_to_Moore.27s_law\"></span><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Relation_to_Moore's_law\">Relation to Moore's law</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Claasen%27s_law&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Relation to Moore&#039;s law\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>In order to achieve a linear improvement in usefulness over time it's necessary to have an exponential increase in technology over time. <a href=\"/wiki/Moore%27s_law\" title=\"Moore&#39;s law\">Moore's law</a> delivers an exponential increase in technology, and so when Claasen's law is combined with Moore's law it implies a linear improvement in usefulness over time.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Notes\">Notes</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Claasen%27s_law&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Notes\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-EDNarticle-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-EDNarticle_1-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\">Dipert, Brian (1999). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.edn.com/electronics-blogs/other/4361480/It-s-elementary\">\"It's elementary\"</a>. <a href=\"/wiki/EDN_(magazine)\" title=\"EDN (magazine)\">EDN Magazine</a><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">2009-01-06</span></span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=It%27s+elementary&amp;rft.pub=EDN+Magazine&amp;rft.date=1999&amp;rft.aulast=Dipert&amp;rft.aufirst=Brian&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.edn.com%2Felectronics-blogs%2Fother%2F4361480%2FIt-s-elementary&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AClaasen%27s+law\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Claasen%27s_law&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/List_of_eponymous_laws\" title=\"List of eponymous laws\">List of eponymous laws</a></li></ul>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw1265\nCached time: 20180909014403\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time usage: 0.040 seconds\nReal time usage: 0.054 seconds\nPreprocessor visited node count: 57/1000000\nPreprocessor generated node count: 0/1500000\nPost\u2010expand include size: 1346/2097152 bytes\nTemplate argument size: 0/2097152 bytes\nHighest expansion depth: 3/40\nExpensive parser function count: 0/500\nUnstrip recursion depth: 0/20\nUnstrip post\u2010expand size: 1079/5000000 bytes\nNumber of Wikibase entities loaded: 0/400\nLua time usage: 0.019/10.000 seconds\nLua memory usage: 1.34 MB/50 MB\n-->\n<!--\nTransclusion expansion time report (%,ms,calls,template)\n100.00%   42.022      1 Template:Cite_web\n100.00%   42.022      1 -total\n-->\n\n<!-- Saved in parser cache with key en